1 [12 points] Compare arrivals from different countries

The arrivals data set comprises quarterly international arrivals (in thousands) to Australia from Japan, New Zealand, UK and the US. In the subsections below, you will:

  • Use autoplot(), ggseasonplot() and ggsubseriesplot() to compare the differences between the arrivals from these four countries.
  • Identify any unusual observations.

Please use the following code sample to support answering the questions below

  1. [2 points] Plot all four countries on a single properly labeled time series plots.

  2. [4 points] Create a properly labeled season plot (ggseasonplot) and subseries plots (ggsubseriesplot) for each of the four countries.

  3. [4 points] Compare and contrast the arrivals to Australia from the four countries using the plots constructed above.

  4. [2 points] Create a ggseasonplot using the polar coordinate for the number of arrivals to Australia from the US. Please identify the outliers year and quarter. Can you explain it?

1.1 [2 points] Solution: Plot all four countries on a single properly labeled time series plots

arrivals_ts <- ts(arrivals, frequency=4, start=1981)
autoplot(arrivals_ts) + ggtitle("Quarterly International Arrivals to Australia (in thoudsands)") + xlab('Year') + ylab("Arrivals (in thousands)")

arrivals_ts <- ts(arrivals, frequency=4, start=1981)
autoplot(arrivals_ts, facets=T) + ggtitle("Quarterly International Arrivals to Australia (in thoudsands)") + xlab('Year') + ylab("Arrivals (in thousands)")

1.7 [4 points] Solution: Compare and constrast the arrivals to Australia from the four contries using the plots constructed above.

Answer: Looking at Season Plots we can see some similarity between Japan and New Zealand on Q3 and Q4 starting on the 1990s, probably because of the proximity of these countries. However, as seen in the subseries plots for both countries, New Zealand has had incremental arrivals throughout all seasons when we compare them year by year in contrast to Japan where we see a decrease on all seasons.

For UK and United States, we can see a similarity, especially around Q4, probably because of the similarity of the holidays in both countries.

We can see the seasonality of the data in the subseries plot of each country. However, is worth noting that japan only has some seasonality as its means are almost the same for all quarters except Q2.

2 [8 points] Random or Not

Using autoplot() and ggAcf() determine whether each of the following datasets can be characterized as white noise:

  1. [4 points] Pigs slaughtered in Victoria, Australia from 1990 onward. Please narrow the dataset using pigs90s <- window(pigs, start=1990) to focus on the 90s.

  2. [4 points] Daily changes in the Down Jones Index. Note that dh contains 292 consecutive trading days so you can use ddj <- diff(dj) to compute the daily changes in the index.

2.1 [2 points] Solution: Pigs slaughtered in Victoria, Australia from 1990 onward

pigs90s <- window(pigs, start=1990)
autoplot(pigs90s) + ggtitle("Subseries Plot for Pigs Slaughtered in Victoria, Australia 1990 onward") + xlab("Year") + ylab("Number of Pigs")

ggAcf(pigs90s, lag.max=68) + ggtitle("ACF Plot for Pigs Slaughtered in Victoria, Australia 1990 onward with 68 ocurrences")

Would you characterize the data as being random? Why?

Answer: Here we see that there are 68 occurrences (Monthly until 1995 for which we have 8 months). We can see here that three of the largest spikes cross the upper bound, which is less than 5% (3/68 = 0.04411). So this can be characterized as white noise since is less than 5%, but is very close to not be white noise.

2.2 [2 points] Solution: Daily changes in the Down Jones Index

ddj <- diff(dj)

autoplot(ddj) + ggtitle("Subseries Plot for Daily Changes in the Down Jones Index") + xlab("Days") + ylab("DDJ")

ggAcf(ddj, lag.max=291) + ggtitle("ACF Plot for Daily Changes in the Down Jones Index")

2.3 [4 points] Daily changes in the Down Jones Index. Note that dh contains 292 consecutive trading days so you can use ddj <- diff(dj) to compute the daily changes in the index.

Would you characterize the data as being random? Why?

Answer: Here we see that there are 291 occurrences. We can see here that six of the largest spikes cross the upper bound, which is less than 5% (6/291 = 0.02061). So this can be characterized as white noise since is less than 5%.
